<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-834-897  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 834 897.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  May 8 1990* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>FCC moves full-speed ahead in deregulation. (FederalCommunications Commission)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Blankenhorn, Dana.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   American Telephone and Telegraph Co. (Rules and regulations).andO;Ticker:    T.andO;Topic:     United States. Federal Communications CommissionDeregulationGovernment RegulationBell Regional Holding CompaniesTelephone companiesLegal IssuesTelecommunications.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>FCC MOVES FULL-SPEED AHEAD IN DEREGULATION WASHINGTON, D.C., U.S.A., 1990 MAY1 (NB) -- U.S.andP;  regulators are moving full-speed ahead to deregulate ATandamp;T,the regional Bell companies, and the international phone networks.andM;In separate actions, the Federal Communications Commission approved the OpenNetwork Architecture plans submitted by seven Regional Bell firms, which willlet them provide enhanced services in their regulated networks in exchangefor offering competitors more access to the network.andP;  A requirement for&quot;structural separation&quot; of units offering plain telephone service andenhanced services will be dropped if the Bells show themselves technicallyprepared to offer the services, with approved federal tariffs showing pricesterms and conditions, and filed state tariffs.andM;The FCC also filled in details of its plan to deregulate ATandamp;T, which wasannounced in March.andP;  A 75-page order would allow ATandamp;T to offer custom,discounted network deals like those in existing tariffs, but without givingmany details and without giving its competitors, primarily MCI and Sprint,the chance to challenge those deals as they do routinely now.andM;Comments to the proposals can be filed through June 12, but the FCC has madeclear its position, that ATandamp;T is no longer a dominant long-distance carrierdespite its market share, variously estimated at two-thirds to three-fourthsof the U.S.andP;  long distance market.andM;On the international front, the U.S.andP;  is investigating whether prices forinternational services exceed costs, and if they do, what can be done aboutit.andP;  UK regulators are working on a similar investigation.andP;  The FCC allegesthat foreign carriers in 1988 collected $2 billion more than U.S.andP;  carriersfor calls made to and from the U.S.andP;  Essentially, the FCC charges thatforeign phone companies, which are connected to national postal services, areusing U.S.andP;  subsidies to keep postage rates down.andM;(Dana Blankenhorn/19900504/Press Contact: FCC, 202-632-7000)</TEXT></DOC>